 name from any of several places in the provinces of Cáceres and Murcia called Cambrón.","Scottish: altered form of   Cameron  .","French: habitational name from any of the places in Somme and Aisne called Cambron. Alternatively, from a diminutive of <i>c(h)ambre</i> ‘room’ (see   Cambre  )."]},{"name":"Camron","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Cameron  ."]}]},{"name":"Sinill","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A female name, another spelling of Sybil, corrupted from Isabel."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Douglas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname borne by one of the most powerful families in Scotland, the earls of Douglas and of Angus, also notorious in earlier times as Border reivers. In the 17th and 18th centuries it was used as a girl's name in northern England. It is now exclusively a boys' name, used throughout the English‐speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sinill Douglas Cameron 1st Chief of Clan Cameron, Mormaer, Dubacan of Angus was born in 1012, in Douglas and Angus, Forfarshire, Scotland, his father, Hugh Cameron Of Angus, was 43 and his mother, Margaret, was 41. He married Marion MacKenneth in 1030, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1050, in his hometown, at the age of 38, and was buried in Douglas and Angus, Forfarshire, Scotland."},"et":{"1012–1050":"1012–1050","1005–Female":"1005–Surnud","1030–1099":"1030–1099","1035–Female":"1035–Surnud","1045–Female":"1045–Surnud","0970–1035":"0970–1035","0972–1031":"0972–1031","before 1012":"enne 1012","1099":"1099","1031":"1031","1030":"1030","1050":"1050","0972":"0972","1005":"1005","0970":"0970","1035":"1035","1012":"1012","1034":"1034","1045":"1045","before 1020":"enne 1020","about 1035":"umbes 1035","before 1030":"1030","about 1031":"umbes 1031","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Scotland","Douglas and Angus, Forfarshire, Scotl